Try to repeat with a map statement

sim_results_df = 
  expand_grid(
    sample_size = 30, #input list, use 30 every single time
    iter = 1:100 #do this 100 times
 ) |> 
  mutate(
    results = map(iter, sim_mean_sd, n_subj = 30) #run sim_mean_sd for every sample size in that column (in this case it's 30 every time, 100 times). saving the results as a dataframe for each of the 100 times you ran the sim.
  ) |> 
  unnest(results) #take all the df's and make it just the sample mean and sd

repeat with a bigger sample size

sim_results_df = 
  expand_grid(
    sample_size = c(30, 60, 90, 120), #i'm doing 100 iterations for each sample size
    iter = 1:1000 
 ) |> 
  mutate(
    results = map(sample_size, sim_mean_sd)
  ) |> 
  unnest(results)

Simple linear regression

sim_df = 
  tibble(
    x = rnorm(30, mean = 1, sd = 1),
    y = 2 + 3 * x + rnorm(30, 0, 1)
  )

sim_df |> 
  ggplot(aes(x = x, y = y)) +
  geom_point()

slr_fit = lm(y ~ x, data = sim_df)

coef(slr_fit)
## (Intercept)           x 
##    2.138406    2.889357

turn this into a function

sim_regression = function(n_subj, beta_0 = 2, beta_1 = 3) {
  
  sim_df = 
     tibble(
       x = rnorm(n_subj, mean = 1, sd = 1),
       y = beta_0 + beta_1 * x + rnorm(30, 0, 1)
     )

slr_fit = lm(y ~ x, data = sim_df)

tibble(
  beta0_hat = coef(slr_fit)[1],
  beta1_hat = coef(slr_fit)[2]
)
}
sim_regression(n_subj = 30)
## # A tibble: 1  2
##   beta0_hat beta1_hat
##       <dbl>     <dbl>
## 1      1.86      3.03

One more example!

The birthday problem - if you put a group of people in a room, what are the chances at least 2 people share a bday? How many people do you need to put in a room to get at least a 50% chance?

birthdays = sample(1:365, 5, replace = TRUE) #there are 365 bdays, sample size 5, and then if you put a number once, you CAN pick it again. This is my data generating system

#is there a repeated bday yes or no?

repeated_bday = length(unique(birthdays)) < 5 # this is the analysis, checking if people have the same bday. If there are less unique bdays than people in the room, you know people share a bday

repeated_bday
## [1] FALSE

put this in a function

bday_sim = function (n_room) {
  
  birthdays = sample(1:365, n_room, replace = TRUE) 

  repeated_bday = length(unique(birthdays)) < n_room
  
  repeated_bday
  
}

bday_sim(20)
## [1] TRUE
bday_sim_results =
  expand_grid(
    bdays = 5:50,
    iter = 1:2500
  ) |> 
  mutate(
    result = map_lgl(bdays, bday_sim)
  ) |> 
  group_by(
    bdays
  ) |> 
  summarize(
    prob_repeat = mean(result)
  )

plot this

bday_sim_results |> 
  ggplot(aes(x = bdays, y = prob_repeat)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_line()
